 To convert Markdown to HTML, you can use a library like `cpp-markdown` or `discount`. However, for a simple and basic conversion, I'll provide a small example using a hand-crafted solution. This example will only cover the most common Markdown elements and won't be exhaustive.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Headers
    std::regex headerRegex(R"(# {1,6}(.*?)(?=\n(?:# {1,6}|$)))");
    std::smatch match;
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, headerRegex)) {
        int level = match.str(0).size() - 1;
        std::string headerContent = match.str(1);
        html += "<h" + std::to_string(level) + ">" + headerContent + "</h" + std::to_string(level) + ">\n";
        markdown.erase(match.first(), match.length());
    }

    // Links
    std::regex linkRegex(R"((https?://[^\s]+))");
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, linkRegex)) {
        std::string link = match.str();
        html += "<a href=\"" + link + "\">" + link + "</a>";
        markdown.erase(match.first(), match.length());
    }

    // Images
    std::regex imageRegex(R"((https?://[^\s]+)(\s+(alt text)))");
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, imageRegex)) {
        std::string link = match.str(1);
        std::string altText = match.str(2);
        html += "<img src=\"" + link + "\" alt=\"" + altText + "\">";
        markdown.erase(match.first(), match.length());
    }

    // Bold and Italic
    std::regex boldRegex(R"((\*\*)(.*?)(?=\*\*|$))");
    std::regex italicRegex(R"(_*(.*?)(?=_*|$))");
    std::sregex_iterator begin(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), boldRegex);
    std::sregex_iterator end;
    while (begin != end) {
        std::string boldContent = begin->str(2);
        html += "<strong>" + boldContent + "</strong>";
        begin++;
    }
    begin = std::sregex_iterator(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), italicRegex);
    while (begin != end) {
        std::string italicContent = begin->str(2);
        html += "<em>" + italicContent + "</em>";
        begin++;
    }

    // Newlines
    html = html.substr(0, html.size() - 1) + "\n";

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!\n\n**Bold text** _Italic text_ [Link](https://example.com)\n\n![Image](https://example.com/image.jpg)";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This example covers headers, links, images, bold, italic, and newlines. It's a simple solution and doesn't cover all Markdown elements, but it should give you a good starting point. For more complex Markdown parsing, consider using a library like `cpp-markdown` or `discount`.

 In Python, both sets and lists are used to store collections of items, but they have distinct differences in their behavior, usage, and internal structure.

1. **Structure**: Lists are ordered, mutable, and allow duplicate elements. They are defined by enclosing the items in square brackets `[]` and separating multiple items with commas. For example: `my_list = [1, 2, 3, "apple", "banana", [4, 5]]`.

   On the other hand, sets are unordered, mutable, and do not allow duplicate elements. They are defined by enclosing the items in curly braces `{}` or by using the `set()` function. For example: `my_set = {1, 2, 3, "apple", "banana"}` or `my_set = set([1, 2, 3, "apple", "banana"])`.

2. **Operations**: Sets have built-in operations for mathematical set operations like union (`|`), intersection (`&`), difference (`-`), and symmetric difference (`^`). For example:

   ```python
   set1 = {1, 2, 3}
   set2 = {3, 4, 5}
   print(set1 | set2)  # {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
   print(set1 & set2)  # {3}
   print(set1 - set2)  # {1, 2}
   print(set1 ^ set2)  # {1, 2, 4, 5}
   ```

   Lists do not have these built-in operations, but you can write functions to perform similar operations.

3. **Performance**: Sets are generally more efficient for operations that require checking membership (`in` or `not in`), as they have a constant average time complexity (O(1)) for these operations due to the absence of duplicates. Lists, on the other hand, have a linear average time complexity (O(n)) for these operations because they need to iterate through the elements.

4. **Iteration**: Both sets and lists can be iterated over, but sets do not maintain the order of the elements, while lists do.

In summary, use lists when you need an ordered collection with duplicate elements and need to preserve the order, and use sets when you need an unordered collection without duplicate elements and want to perform set operations or check membership quickly.

